alternatives.transcript: sixty two year old patient leslie presents to the emergency room for dyspnea and fatigue patient states that his symptoms began two weeks ago and he went to his primary care three days ago and was informed to go to the emergency room he noticed that his symptoms have worsened today he states that his shortness of breath occurs when he is exercising but not at rest and his nyha functional classification was a level two he has not taken anything for his symptoms positive ros symptoms included palpitations pre syncope fatigue wheezing and dizziness all other ros symptoms were negative patient has a past medical history of hypertension and is currently taking lisinopril ten milligrams daily for it he describes his diet as balanced and states he used to exercise daily with walking until his symptoms started and he's no longer because of the shortness of breath he denies alcohol tobacco or illicit drug use he's an elementary school teacher and he's married and currently lives with his wife he notes he has had a previous catheterization completed which was normal but denies any other hospitalizations or surgeries family history included his mother dying at the age of forty due to sudden death and his father dying at the age of fifty nine due to a heart attack on the physical exam it was noted that there was no jvd no carotid bruise a regular heart rate with a positive systolic murmur with an s four sound positive for gallops but no friction rubs there was no chest roll tenderness calf was nontender lungs were cleared to auscultation bilaterally and it was negative for lower extremity edema and his pulses were full bilaterally in his extremities the x-ray showed cardiomegaly and his echo showed left ventricular asymmetric hypertrophy with an ejection fraction of sixty percent his ekg shows normal sinus rhythm with meeting the lvh criteria with tall r waves in the septal waves his vitals upon entering the room was a heart rate of a hundred and ten his blood pressure a hundred and thirty over ninety oxygen stats of ninety six respiratory rate of sixteen and temperature of ninety eight point six patient was admitted to telemetry and his medications upon admission were to discontinue lisinopril and to give disopyramide a hundred milligrams he's given a saline lock kbo and vitals will be taken every two hours with strict eye and a input and output and daily weight dvt prophylaxis and oxygen via nasal nasal cannula and maintaining o two sat over ninety six percent he will have a normal diet and activity as tolerated patient was also referred to cardiothoracic surgeon for surgical myomectomy and alcohol injection and as well as an interventional cardiologist for an aicd evaluation patient was diagnosed with familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
